{"add":{"doc":{"id":"6b0f654698e106427410c522f6aff76f86e5c43437a7c605484cc816bf581405","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/DJ_Joe_Mfalme_DJ_Purpl_Scratching_on_Pioneer_CDJ_2000_%26_CDJ_850.webm/220px--DJ_Joe_Mfalme_DJ_Purpl_Scratching_on_Pioneer_CDJ_2000_%26_CDJ_850.webm.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Scratching, sometimes referred to as scrubbing, is a DJ and turntablist technique used to produce distinctive sounds by moving a vinyl record back and forth on a turntable while optionally manipulating the crossfader on a DJ mixer. While scratching is most commonly associated with hip hop music, since the mid-1970s, it has been used in some styles of pop and in nu metal. Within hip hop culture, scratching is one of the measures of a DJ's skills, as in DMC World DJ Championship or IDA (International DJ Association) former ITF (International turntablist Federation) where the DJs can use only scratch oriented gear (turntables + mixer + digital vinyl systems or vinyl only), and there are many scratching competitions."]}}}